          </div>
        </header>

        <!-- Content -->
        <div class="prose max-w-none text-gray-300 leading-relaxed space-y-6">

          <p class="text-lg">
            Vibe coding has changed the game. Tools like Cursor, GitHub Copilot, and Claude let anyone go from idea to working prototype in hours instead of months. That's genuinely amazing.
          </p>
          <p>
            But there's a gap — a big one — between "it works on my laptop" and "it's ready for thousands of users to depend on." We've audited dozens of vibecoded projects at this point, and the same patterns keep showing up. Here are the five that bite hardest.
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-fira text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4" id="error-handling">1. Error handling is the happy path</h2>
          <p>
            AI-generated code is optimistic code. It writes the path where everything goes right — the API responds, the network is fast, the user enters valid data, and the device has plenty of memory.
          </p>
          <p>
            In the real world? The API times out. The user is on a train going through a tunnel. They paste an emoji into a phone number field. Their phone has 12 apps running in the background.
          </p>
          <p>
            What we typically see in vibecoded projects:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
            <li>No retry logic on network requests — one timeout and the app silently fails</li>
            <li>Unhandled exceptions that crash the app instead of showing a user-friendly error</li>
            <li>Missing input validation — or validation that only runs client-side</li>
            <li>No offline state handling at all</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-white">The fix:</strong> Error handling isn't glamorous, but it's the difference between a 2-star and 5-star app. Every network call needs a failure path. Every user input needs validation. Every state transition needs a "what if this goes wrong?" branch. This is where experienced developers earn their keep — not in writing the feature, but in making the feature survive contact with reality.
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-fira text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4" id="security">2. Security is an afterthought (or not a thought at all)</h2>
          <p>
            This is the scariest one. AI coding tools will happily generate code that stores API keys in plain text, skips authentication checks, or trusts client-side data for authorization decisions. It doesn't know any better — it's pattern-matching on training data, and a lot of tutorial code is insecure.
          </p>
          <p>
            Things we've found in real vibecoded projects:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
            <li>API keys hardcoded in the client app (extractable by anyone with a decompiler)</li>
            <li>No server-side validation — the app trusts whatever the client sends</li>
            <li>Authentication tokens stored in plain SharedPreferences or localStorage</li>
            <li>SQL queries built with string concatenation (yes, SQL injection still exists)</li>
            <li>Missing rate limiting on endpoints, inviting abuse</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-white">The fix:</strong> A security audit before launch isn't optional — it's a responsibility to your users. Move secrets server-side. Validate everything on the backend. Use proper token storage. Run dependency vulnerability scans. If you're handling any user data at all, this stuff matters legally too (GDPR, CCPA, app store policies).
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-fira text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4" id="architecture">3. The architecture is a house of cards</h2>
          <p>
            When you're vibecoding, you're having a conversation. "Add a login screen." "Now connect it to Firebase." "Add a profile page that shows the user's posts." Each prompt builds on the last, and the AI obliges.
          </p>
          <p>
            The result? An app that works but has no real architecture. Everything is coupled to everything. The login screen directly references the database. The UI layer contains business logic. State is scattered across global variables, singletons, and random static fields.
          </p>
          <p>
            This doesn't matter for a demo. It matters enormously when you need to:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
            <li>Add a new feature without breaking three existing ones</li>
            <li>Write tests (you can't unit test code that depends on the entire app)</li>
            <li>Onboard another developer who needs to understand the codebase</li>
            <li>Swap out a backend service or upgrade a dependency</li>
            <li>Debug a production issue at 2 AM</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-white">The fix:</strong> You don't need to rewrite from scratch — but you do need to introduce boundaries. Separate your data layer from your UI. Use dependency injection so components aren't hardwired together. Establish clear module boundaries. This is refactoring work that pays for itself within weeks.
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-fira text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4" id="performance">4. Performance is death by a thousand cuts</h2>
          <p>
            AI-generated code tends to be... verbose. It reaches for the straightforward solution, which is often the least efficient one. On a modern MacBook, you'll never notice. On a mid-range Android phone with 3GB of RAM? You'll notice.
          </p>
          <p>
            Common performance issues we see:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
            <li>Loading entire datasets into memory when only a page is needed</li>
            <li>Redundant API calls — fetching the same data multiple times per screen</li>
            <li>No image optimization — loading 4000×3000 photos into a 200px thumbnail</li>
            <li>UI recomposition/re-rendering on every state change (not just relevant ones)</li>
            <li>Memory leaks from listeners, callbacks, or coroutines that never get cleaned up</li>
            <li>No caching strategy at all — every screen load is a fresh network round trip</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-white">The fix:</strong> Profile before you optimize, but do profile. Use the platform tools (Android Studio Profiler, Xcode Instruments, Chrome DevTools). Implement pagination. Add a caching layer. Optimize images. The goal isn't perfection — it's making sure the app feels snappy on the devices your actual users have, not just your development machine.
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-fira text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4" id="app-store">5. App store compliance is a brick wall</h2>
          <p>
            You've built the app. It works. You're ready to ship. You submit to the App Store or Google Play and... rejected.
          </p>
          <p>
            Apple and Google have extensive (and evolving) review guidelines that AI tools don't account for. The AI doesn't know that your app needs a privacy policy, or that you can't use certain APIs without justification, or that your in-app purchases need to go through the platform's billing system.
          </p>
          <p>
            Common rejection reasons for vibecoded apps:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-400">
            <li>Missing or inadequate privacy policy</li>
            <li>Using restricted APIs (background location, health data, contacts) without proper justification</li>
            <li>In-app purchases that bypass the platform's payment system</li>
            <li>Missing accessibility features (VoiceOver/TalkBack support)</li>
            <li>Insufficient content moderation for user-generated content</li>
            <li>Crash on review — the app works in development but crashes on the reviewer's device</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            <strong class="text-white">The fix:</strong> Read the guidelines before you build, not after. But if you're already past that point, a compliance review before submission saves you weeks of back-and-forth with review teams. We've shipped dozens of apps through both stores and know exactly what the reviewers look for.
          </p>

          <hr class="border-dark-700 my-12">

          <h2 class="font-fira text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-12 mb-4">The bottom line</h2>
          <p>
            Vibe coding is a legitimate superpower. The ability to go from idea to prototype in a weekend is transformative, and it's only going to get better. But prototypes aren't products, and the gap between them is exactly where bugs, security holes, and one-star reviews live.
          </p>
          <p>
            The good news? You don't have to throw away what you've built. Most vibecoded projects have a solid core — the idea is sound, the basic flows work, the UI is often surprisingly good. What they need is an experienced eye to find the landmines before your users do.
          </p>
          <p>
            That's what we do at Commit 451. We take vibecoded projects and make them production-ready — not by starting over, but by surgically fixing the things that matter. Code audit, architecture cleanup, security hardening, performance optimization, and app store launch support.
          </p>
          <p class="text-lg">
            <strong class="text-white">Built something with AI and ready to take it to the next level?</strong>
